ions of metropolitan life. The author's interdisciplinary approach situates the careers and visual strategies of illustrators such as Paul Gavarni and Achille Devéria in a broader context of urban entertainments and social practices; it brings to light a rich terrain of artistic collaboration and commercial experimentation that linked the worlds of art, literature, fashion, publicity, and the theatre. A timely historical meditation on the emergence of a commercial visual culture that prefigured our own, Graphic Culture traces the promotional power of artistic celebrities and the crucial perceptual and social transformations generated by new media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and societyzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommercial artzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommunication and culturezFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommunication and culturezFrancezParisy19th century. 0aGraphic artistszFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrints, FrenchzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrints, FrenchzFrancezParisy19th century. 0aVisual communicationzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 7aART / European.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355514340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555143/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles